Your Honor,

I, Chloe Mills, stand before you today, pleading guilty to the offense of affray. I would like to provide context to the events that unfolded that night, as it pertains to my involvement.

On the night in question, I had just discovered that my boyfriend had betrayed my trust by cheating on me. Overwhelmed by a mix of emotions, including anger and hurt, I made the unfortunate decision to confront him at the bar where he was with his friends. However, I want to stress that my intention was never to cause physical harm, but rather to seek answers and closure.

During my time at the bar, I admit that my emotions got the better of me. I raised my voice and threatened to retrieve a gun and shoot my boyfriend if he did not disclose the other woman's name. It is important to note that these were empty threats, as I neither possess nor have access to a firearm. Regrettably, my words caused distress among the other patrons present, and for that, I offer my deepest apologies.

I understand that my behavior at the bar was unacceptable and did not contribute positively to the situation. I realize now that there were alternative, more constructive ways to handle the circumstances. I genuinely regret the fear and discomfort I caused others.

In my defense, I wish to emphasize that, prior to this incident, I have maintained a clean criminal record. I have always endeavored to be a law-abiding citizen and make positive contributions to society. As a testament to my commitment to personal growth and improvement, I currently attend therapy sessions once a week.

I stand here today to express my remorse for my actions and to take full responsibility for the distress I caused during the altercation. I deeply regret my behavior and acknowledge the need for better judgment in difficult situations. This incident has served as a wake-up call, reminding me of the importance of personal growth and self-control.

I ask the court to consider my guilty plea as a genuine act of remorse and acceptance of responsibility for my actions. I have already taken steps towards personal development and am willing to continue therapy as a means of further self-improvement.

I am aware of the impact my conduct had on those present at the bar, and I have since suffered the consequences of my actions. The weight of the fear and discomfort I caused has been a heavy burden to bear.

As I stand before you today, I humbly request your leniency, taking into account my lack of prior criminal history, my commitment to addressing personal issues, and my sincere regret for the distress I caused. I wholeheartedly aim to make amends and become a better member of society.

Thank you for affording me the opportunity to express myself and considering the circumstances surrounding this unfortunate incident.

